SGID Bit:
---------

-> Stands for Set Group ID.

-> When SGID bit is set on a directory any new file or sub-directory created will inherit the directory's group ownership.

-> To set the SGID bit:

    Method 1:
            chmod 2XXX <directory>

    Method 2:
            chmod g+s <directory>

SUID Bit:
---------

-> Command will be running with Owner rights instead of the rights of the executer.

-> To set SUID bit:

    # chmod u+s <file-name>

Sticky Bit:
-----------

-> In Linux, the sticky bit is a special file system permission applied to directories that prevents users from deleting or renaming files they do not own, even if they have full write access to that directory.

-> Lowercase t: The sticky bit is active, and the "others" group also has execution (x) permissions.

-> Uppercase T: The sticky bit is active, but the "others" group does not have execution permissions.

-> How to set Sticky bit:

    # chmod +t <directory>

-> How to remove Sticky bit:

    # chmod -t <directory>

